The user is asking about how to recognize and show craftsmanship in their platform - specifically for writing, drawing, and guided facilitation for cohorts. They want to understand what makes something "well-crafted" and how to make that visible in their system.

This is a deep question about quality, attention, and care in digital artifacts. Let me think about what makes craftsmanship visible and recognizable.## What Makes Craftsmanship Visible?

You can TELL good craftsmanship through specific markers that reveal care, attention, and mastery. Let me break down what these are and how to surface them digitally.

## The Markers of Craft in Different Media

### In Writing
**What reveals craft:**
- Rhythm variations (not monotonous sentence length)
- Deliberate word choices (crossing out "walked" for "ambled")
- Structural integrity (callbacks, echoes, threads)
- Breathing room (knowing when NOT to write)
- Revision traces (this paragraph was rewritten 4 times)

### In Drawing
**What reveals craft:**
- Line confidence (no hesitation marks vs. thoughtful exploration)
- Pressure variation (shows control and intention)
- Negative space usage (what's NOT drawn matters)
- Gesture economy (saying more with less)
- Iteration visible (ghost lines from attempts)

### In Teaching/Facilitation
**What reveals craft:**
- Wait time (letting silence do work)
- Question scaffolding (building from where students are)
- Responsive pivoting (changing based on the room)
- Energy management (knowing when to push/rest)
- Attention distribution (noticing who's quiet)

## How to Make Craft Visible in Your System

### 1. The Attention Heatmap
```typescript
interface CraftMarkers {
  attention_density: {
    // Where did they spend time?
    zones: Array<{
      area: BoundingBox;
      duration_ms: number;
      revision_count: number;
      pause_count: number;
    }>;
  };

  revision_archaeology: {
    // What did they change and why?
    layers: Array<{
      timestamp: number;
      before: string;
      after: string;
      duration_of_consideration: number;
    }>;
  };

  rhythm_signature: {
    // What's their breathing pattern?
    sentence_lengths: number[];
    paragraph_breaks: number[];
    drawing_stroke_velocities: number[];
  };
}
```

### 2. The Craft Overlay (Visual)

```tsx
// When viewing someone's work, toggle "craft view"
function CraftView({ work }) {
  return (
    <div className="craft-overlay">
      {/* Show where they lingered */}
      <AttentionHeatmap zones={work.attention_density} />

      {/* Show revision depth */}
      <RevisionLayers 
        layers={work.revisions}
        view="ghosted" // See all versions simultaneously
      />

      {/* Show rhythm */}
      <RhythmVisualization 
        pattern={work.rhythm_signature}
        as="musical_notation" // Or "heartbeat" or "wave"
      />

      {/* Show doubt/confidence */}
      <ConfidenceTrace 
        moments={work.marks.filter(m => m.type === 'pause')}
      />
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 3. The Facilitation Craft (Your Cohort Journal)

For guided cohort facilitation, craft shows in:

```typescript
interface FacilitationCraft {
  pacing: {
    prompt_release: "timed" | "responsive" | "emergent";
    wait_time_after_prompt: number;  // Patience
    response_before_next: boolean;   // Listening
  };

  attention: {
    who_hasn't_spoken: string[];
    response_patterns: Map<user, ResponsePattern>;
    energy_level: "building" | "sustained" | "waning";
  };

  scaffolding: {
    prompt_complexity: number;  // Increases over time?
    support_given: Array<{
      to_whom: string;
      type: "example" | "rephrase" | "encouragement";
      timing: "preemptive" | "just_in_time" | "followup";
    }>;
  };

  responsiveness: {
    pivots: Array<{
      original_plan: string;
      what_happened: string;
      new_direction: string;
      why: string;  // "Group needed more foundation"
    }>;
  };
}
```

## The Cohort Journal System (With Craft)

Here's how to build facilitated cohort journals that show craft:

### The Facilitator's Dashboard
```tsx
function CohortFacilitatorView({ cohort }) {
  const [promptStrategy, setPromptStrategy] = useState('responsive');
  const [attention, setAttention] = useState(new Map());

  return (
    <div className="facilitator-craft-bench">
      {/* See who needs attention */}
      <AttentionRadar>
        {cohort.members.map(member => (
          <ParticipantPulse
            member={member}
            lastActive={member.last_activity}
            contributions={member.contribution_count}
            struggling={detectStruggling(member)}
          />
        ))}
      </AttentionRadar>

      {/* Craft the next prompt based on energy */}
      <PromptCrafter>
        <EnergyMeter current={cohort.energy_level} />
        <SuggestedPrompts based_on={cohort.recent_themes} />
        <TimingDecision>
          {promptStrategy === 'responsive' && (
            <div>Wait until 80% have responded to current</div>
          )}
        </TimingDecision>
      </PromptCrafter>

