  continues?: PageId;   // Links to previous page
  responds_to?: PageId; // If it's a reply
  series?: string;      // "Daily Math Thoughts"
}
```

**Organic composition:**
```javascript
// System detects patterns
function suggestComposition(pages) {
  // Notice daily pattern?
  if (hasDaily(pages)) {
    suggest("Make this a daily journal?");
  }

  // Notice topic cluster?
  if (hasCommonTopic(pages)) {
    suggest("Compile into a book on ${topic}?");
  }

  // Notice Q&A pattern?
  if (hasResponsePattern(pages)) {
    suggest("Create a correspondence course?");
  }
}
```

## Approach 3: The Workshop (Craft Metaphor)

```
RAW MATERIALS (pages) → ASSEMBLY TABLE → FINISHED WORKS

Your pages are raw materials.
The assembly table lets you arrange them.
You decide what they become.
```

**The Assembly Interface:**
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ ASSEMBLY TABLE                          │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Your Pages:                            │
│ □ Jan 15 - Slope thoughts              │
│ □ Jan 16 - Derivative drawing          │
│ □ Jan 17 - Question about limits       │
│ □ Jan 18 - Letter to prof             │
│                                        │
│ [Select pages and choose:]             │
│                                        │
│ → Make Journal (recurring prompts)     │
│ → Make Book (chapters)                 │
│ → Make Course (lessons)                │
│ → Send Letter (one-time)              │
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## The Unified Solution: Pages as Atoms

**Every page has these capabilities:**

```typescript
interface SmartPage {
  // Core content
  id: string;
  content: string;
  drawings: any[];

  // Temporal metadata
  created_at: Date;
  edited_at: Date;
  published_at?: Date;

  // Semantic metadata
  type?: 'reflection' | 'lesson' | 'question' | 'response';
  topic_tags: string[];
  responding_to?: PageId;

  // Composition hints
  series_name?: string;     // "Daily Math"
  sequence_number?: number;  // Day 3
  intended_for?: string[];   // ["@sarah", "calc-class"]

  // Publication status
  visibility: 'private' | 'shared' | 'public';
  published_as?: {
    type: 'journal' | 'book' | 'course' | 'letter';
    work_id: string;
    position: number;
  }[];
}
```

## How Publishing Works (From Pages)

### Creating a Journal from Pages
```javascript
// You've written 7 pages tagged #daily-reflection
const pages = await db.pages.where({ 
  tags: 'daily-reflection',
  author: userId 
});

// System suggests
"You have 7 daily reflections. Create a journal?"

// You accept
const journal = await createJournal({
  title: "My Daily Reflections",
  pages: pages.map(p => p.id),
  schedule: 'daily',
  start_date: pages[0].created_at
});

// Now others can subscribe
// They'll get one page per day
```

### Creating a Book from Pages
```javascript
// You've written 20 pages about calculus
const pages = await db.pages.where({ 
  tags: 'calculus',
  author: userId 
});

// Arrange into chapters
const book = await createBook({
  title: "Visual Calculus",
  chapters: [
    { title: "What is Slope?", pages: [1, 2, 3] },
    { title: "Understanding Derivatives", pages: [4, 5, 6] },
    // ...
  ]
});
```

## The UI Flow

```
1. WRITE naturally in pages
   → Like a notebook, no structure required

2. NOTICE patterns emerge
   → System suggests: "These could be a journal"

3. COMPOSE into structures
   → Drag pages into journal/book/course template

4. PUBLISH for others
   → Share link, people subscribe/read

5. CONTINUE writing pages
   → Add to existing works or start new ones
```

## The Database (Page-Centric)

```sql
-- Just pages and compositions
CREATE TABLE pages (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
  author_id UUID,
  content TEXT,
  drawings JSONB,

  -- Metadata
  created_at TIMESTAMP,
  tags TEXT[],
  series_name TEXT,
  sequence_number INT,

  -- Can be in multiple publications
  published_in JSONB  -- [{type: 'journal', id: 'xxx', position: 3}]
);

CREATE TABLE compositions (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
  type ENUM('journal', 'book', 'course', 'letter'),
  title TEXT,
  author_id UUID,

  -- References to pages
  page_ids UUID[],
  structure JSONB,  -- How pages are organized

  -- Publishing
  slug TEXT UNIQUE,
  published BOOLEAN
);
```

This is how normal writing works:
1. You write when inspired (pages)
2. You notice themes emerging
3. You organize into collections
4. You share what feels complete

The platform just needs to support this natural flow.

